{"timestamp": "2025-12-04 10:53:04.683295", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nSummary of the Network State\n- Control plane: EBGP adjacencies across leaves, spines, and super-spine appear established and exchanging routes.\n- Data plane: End-to-end host connectivity is broken between pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2) and pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2). Additionally, pc_0_1 cannot reach its default gateway (10.0.1.1).\n\nDetected Anomalies\n- Host-to-host reachability fails:\n  - pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1 ping: timeout.\n  - pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0 ping: timeout.\n- Host-to-default-gateway behavior is asymmetric:\n  - pc_0_0 -> 10.0.0.1: OK (2/2 replies).\n  - pc_0_1 -> 10.0.1.1: no response (timeout).\n- leaf_router_0_1 cannot ping its directly connected host:\n  - On leaf_router_0_1, ping 10.0.1.2 fails with “ping: connect: Invalid argument”.\n\nKey Findings and Evidence\n- Hosts are correctly addressed and linked:\n  - pc_0_0: 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1. Link up. Can ping 10.0.0.1.\n  - pc_0_1: 10.0.1.2/24, default via 10.0.1.1. Link up. ARP for 10.0.1.1 resolves to 66:96:01:2d:bb:e0 (leaf_router_0_1 eth2), but ping fails.\n- leaf_router_0_1 configuration and routing table show a conflicting blackhole:\n  - Running config includes:\n    - ip route 10.0.1.0/30 Null0\n    - router bgp 65201 … network 10.0.1.0/24 and network 10.0.1.0/30\n  - Kernel routing on leaf_router_0_1:\n    - blackhole 10.0.1.0/30 proto static\n    - 10.0.1.0/24 dev eth2 (connected)\n  - Effect: 10.0.1.0/30 (more specific) covers 10.0.1.0–10.0.1.3 including host 10.0.1.2 and the gateway 10.0.1.1. The blackhole takes precedence for those destinations, dropping locally originated and forwarded traffic to 10.0.1.2 and potentially affecting responses to 10.0.1.1.\n  - Direct evidence: ping from leaf_router_0_1 to 10.0.1.2 returns “Invalid argument,” a typical symptom when the route to the destination is a blackhole.\n- Erroneous propagation of the more-specific blackhole via BGP:\n  - Other routers’ RIBs contain both 10.0.1.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/30 learned via BGP. For example:\n    - leaf_router_0_0: B>* 10.0.1.0/30 via 172.16.0.4 and B>* 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4.\n    - spines and super-spine also show 10.0.1.0/30 as BGP-learned.\n  - Network-wide effect: Traffic to 10.0.1.2 is drawn by the more-specific /30 toward leaf_router_0_1, where it is then blackholed.\n\nLocalization of Fault\n- Faulty device: leaf_router_0_1.\n- Faulty subsystem: Routing configuration (static route and BGP advertisement).\n\nRoot Cause\n- Misconfiguration on leaf_router_0_1 introducing a blackhole for 10.0.1.0/30 and advertising that blackhole (/30) via BGP:\n  - ip route 10.0.1.0/30 Null0\n  - network 10.0.1.0/30 in BGP\n- This conflicts with the intended design (each leaf should advertise only its host /24) and specifically blackholes the first four IPs of the leaf’s local /24, including the host (10.0.1.2) and gateway (10.0.1.1).\n\nImpact Assessment\n- Local impact: pc_0_1 cannot reliably reach or be reached; even gateway reachability fails due to blackhole preference for replies to 10.0.1.2.\n- Network-wide impact: All nodes prefer the more-specific 10.0.1.0/30 route, causing traffic destined to 10.0.1.2 to be forwarded to leaf_router_0_1 and then dropped. This breaks inter-host connectivity across the fabric for that host subnet segment.\n\nOverall Health\n- Control plane: BGP adjacencies are up and exchanging routes as designed (except the extra/incorrect /30 being advertised).\n- Data plane: Connectivity degraded specifically for the 10.0.1.0/30 slice due to the blackhole. The rest of the fabric appears operational.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 9844, "output_tokens": 4537, "total_tokens": 14381, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9728}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3392}}}
